  "theory": "The Intel 8085 is a 40-pin Dual In-line Package (DIP) 8-bit microprocessor. The 40 pins can be classified into six functional groups:\n\n1. Address Bus:\n- Pins 21 to 28 (A8 to A15): Upper 8 bits of the address bus. These are output pins and carry the most significant 8 bits of memory/IO address. They remain active during the entire machine cycle.\n\n2. Multiplexed Address/Data Bus:\n- Pins 12 to 19 (AD0 to AD7): Lower 8 bits of the address bus multiplexed with the 8-bit data bus. During the T1 state of a machine cycle, these lines carry the lower 8 bits of address (synchronized with ALE = 1). During T2 and T3 states, they serve as the bidirectional data bus.\n\n3. Control and Status Signals:\n- ALE (Address Latch Enable): Pin 30. A positive pulse sent by the CPU to indicate that AD0-AD7 carry a valid address. It is used to latch the address into external registers (e.g., 74LS373).\n- RD̄ (Read): Pin 32. Output, active-low. Indicates that the selected memory or I/O device is to be read.\n- WR̄ (Write): Pin 31. Output, active-low. Indicates that data on the data bus is to be written into the selected memory or I/O location.\n- IO/M̄: Pin 34. Output status line. High indicates an I/O operation, and Low indicates a memory operation.\n- S1 and S0: Pins 33 and 29. Status signals that define the current machine cycle state (e.g., Opcode Fetch: S1=1, S0=1; Memory Read: S1=1, S0=0; Memory Write: S1=0, S0=1; Halt: S1=0, S0=0).\n\n4. Power Supply and Clock Signals:\n- VCC: Pin 40. +5V power supply input.\n- VSS: Pin 20. Ground reference (0V).\n- X1 and X2: Pins 1 and 2. Crystal inputs. A crystal oscillator or RC network is connected here to set the internal clock frequency (the internal frequency is half of the crystal frequency, e.g., a 6 MHz crystal yields a 3 MHz CPU clock).\n- CLK (OUT): Pin 37. System clock output to synchronize other peripheral devices with the processor.\n\n5. Interrupts and Peripheral Signals:\n- TRAP: Pin 6. Highest priority, non-maskable vectored interrupt (edge and level triggered).\n- RST 7.5: Pin 7. Maskable vectored interrupt (rising edge triggered).\n- RST 6.5: Pin 8. Maskable vectored interrupt (high level triggered).\n- RST 5.5: Pin 9. Maskable vectored interrupt (high level triggered).\n- INTR: Pin 10. Maskable general-purpose interrupt request.\n- INTĀ: Pin 11. Interrupt acknowledge output (active low), used to read the opcode/vector from the interrupting device.\n\n6. DMA (Direct Memory Access) Signals:\n- HOLD: Pin 39. Input requesting DMA controller to gain control of address and data buses.\n- HLDA (Hold Acknowledge): Pin 38. Output indicating the CPU has released the buses for DMA.\n\n7. Reset Signals:\n- RESET IN̄: Pin 36. Input, active-low. Resets the Program Counter to 0000H and clears interrupts.\n- RESET OUT: Pin 3. Output, active-high. Indicates the CPU is being reset and can reset other system components.",
